# {{name}}

Rosette photonic design project. Python scripts in `designs/` produce GDSII layout files.

## ALWAYS read the reference files before coding

Before writing or modifying any Rosette code, read these files:

- `.rosette/api.pyi` -- complete typed API (source of truth for all classes and functions)
- `rosette.toml` -- project config, layer definitions (named layers), DRC rules, DFM config
- `components/` -- editable component source

Your training data may be outdated -- these files match your installed version.

## ALWAYS build then check

A design is not complete until it passes checks. After every build, run checks and fix any violations before presenting the result:

```
uv run rosette build designs/foo.py
uv run rosette check designs/foo.py
```

A passing build only means the GDS was written -- it does NOT mean the design is correct. `rosette check` catches DRC violations (min width, spacing, overlap), unconnected ports, width mismatches, and bend radius violations.

## Key conventions

- All coordinates are in microns
- Designs must export a `design` variable (a `Cell` instance)
- Use `from rosette import *` for core types (Cell, Layer, Point, Route, etc.)
- Use `load_layer_map()` to access layers by name from rosette.toml (e.g. `layers.silicon.layer`)
- DRC and DFM sections in rosette.toml accept layer names (e.g. `[drc.layers.silicon]`)
- Use `from components import mmi_1x2, ring, grating_coupler` for local components
- Components follow a consistent API: first param is `layer`, second is `width`
- Always prefix CLI commands with `uv run` (e.g. `uv run rosette build designs/foo.py`)
- The package is `librosette` (installed via `uv add librosette`, imported as `rosette`)
- For in-script DRC: `load_drc_rules()` and `run_drc()`
- Grating couplers must be spaced at least 127 um apart (standard fiber array pitch). Use S-bend routes to fan out from closely-spaced component ports to the GC pitch
- LSP errors on `from rosette import ...` are expected (native extension); ignore them

